liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Joining once again from overseas, Genesis Owusu celebrates! "It's really about humanity and our stubborn perseverance to wake up every day and make it through," he says. "It's about the strength of community." He goes on to call for a ceasefire in Gaza. "Ceasefire now, ceasefire now, ceasefire now," he says. "Free Palestine."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: WINNER: Album of the Year — Genesis Owusu — STRUGGLER

children.content: Joining once again from overseas, Genesis Owusu celebrates!
"It's really about humanity and our stubborn perseverance to wake up every day and make it through," he says.
"It's about the strength of community."
He goes on to call for a ceasefire in Gaza.
"Ceasefire now, ceasefire now, ceasefire now," he says.
"Free Palestine."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: WOW, WOW, and WOW! That's four for Troye! This man is unstoppable. Presented by Missy Higgins, he was speechless. "Guys I said everything before, I don't know what else to say," he said. "I'm excited for the future of Australian music. "I swear I'm not bragging, but Kylie Minogue and I are nominated in the same category in the Grammys, and I'm just so proud."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: WINNER: Troye Sivan — Best Solo Artist

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Aussie rock world beaters Jet are inducted into the ARIA Hall of Fame, 20 years on from the release of their enormous debut album Get Born. Frontman Nic Cester ends his speech reflecting on the power of music to bring people together in difficult times. "There are some truly tragic, atrocious things taking place around the world," he said. "It's often in moments like this I'm reminded of the importance of art and music. Music has always been an antidote in our lives during troubled moments. "A place of refuge where thoughts, feelings and emotions can be processed and sometimes shared in a way that can bring people together."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Jet earn their place in the ARIA Hall of Fame

image.altText: A satellite photo showing the Al-Shifa hospital complex in Gaza, surrounded by suburban rooftops

props.synopsis: The Israeli military launches a "precise and targeted operation" inside Gaza's Al-Shifa Hospital. Follow live.

title.children: Israeli military forces raid Gaza's largest hospital in operation against Hamas

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israeli soldiers say they killed several Hamas militants at the outset of the raid on Al-Shifa hospital. "Before entering the hospital our forces were confronted by explosive devices and terrorist squads, fighting ensued in which terrorists were killed," the Israeli military said, without specifying exactly where the firefight took place. Israeli Army Radio say five militants had been killed and that weapons were found inside the Al-Shifa compound. Hamas has repeatedly denied that its fighters operate out of hospital grounds. Reporting with Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: IDF says it engaged in fight with Hamas militants before Al-Shifa raid

children.content: Israeli soldiers say they killed several Hamas militants at the outset of the raid on Al-Shifa hospital.

"Before entering the hospital our forces were confronted by explosive devices and terrorist squads, fighting ensued in which terrorists were killed," the Israeli military said, without specifying exactly where the firefight took place.
Israeli Army Radio say five militants had been killed and that weapons were found inside the Al-Shifa compound.
Hamas has repeatedly denied that its fighters operate out of hospital grounds.
Reporting with Reuters

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A member of Hamas' political office says Israel's attempt to portray its "incursion" inside Al-Shifa hospital as a success is "politically juvenile" and "an exposed theatrical move which won't work on anyone". In a video seen by the ABC, Ezzat Al-Racheq says Al-Shifa is sheltering ill and injured people, alongside displaced Gazans, doctors and nurses. "The arrival of the occupations tanks to the Shifa is not an achievement, for the Shifa is a civilian medical refuge and not a military barracks," he said. "And Netanyahu and his army's attempts to depict that as an achievement or victory, demonstrates failure, confusion and the depth of their defeat that they are incurring." Al-Racheq also said the US's readiness to go along with claims Hamas uses the hospitals, made President Joe Biden a "full partner with the occupation in this crime".
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israel's military operation in Al-Shifa 'not an achievement', Hamas says

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israel has repeatedly said Hamas is using underground tunnels in Al-Shifa to hide, which they say has led to this military operation. But this is not the first time Israel has said that. They previously said Hamas used underground areas in Al-Shifa during a 2008-2009 war, according to Reuters. That war saw more than 1,400 Palestinians and 13 Israelis killed. It was not possible to verify the claims at the time, Reuters says. The New York Times says one of their journalists in 2008 watched armed Hamas militants walking around Al-Shifa Hospital in civilian clothes. Amnesty Internationa l concluded in the 2014 conflict that Hamas used parts of Al-Shifa "to detain, interrogate, torture and otherwise ill-treat suspects, even as other parts of the hospital continued to function as a medical center".
